Post Caption: My Top 5 Smart Home Tech Essentials:  Building a smart home used to be something that needed to be built into the foundations of your home. But now with ecosystems like Apple HomeKit and Amazon Alexa it‚Äôs so easy to start creating your dream home! Items in this video: Apple TV 4K Nanoleaf RGB lightstrip (HomeKit enabled) Nanoleaf Shapes (HomeKit enabled) Dyson V15 Detect Apple HomePod Mini If you‚Äôre interested in these items check the link in my bio and let me know if you want to see more smart home tech content!  #smarthome #tech #hometech #smarthometechnology #homekit #techtok #apple #smarttech #technology
Keywords: smarthome, tech, hometech, smarthometechnology, homekit, techtok, apple, smarttech, technology
transcript: These are my top 5 smart home tech essentials to enhance your living experience. At number 1 is the Apple TV 4K, this is a great addition to the Apple ecosystem with built in Siri, HomeKit, Control and even FaceTime, and the operating system is miles ahead of any other smart TVs out there, most importantly it won't break the bank, they start from just ¬£149 and are a great gift for anyone. Next up is lighting, this can really help enhance the mood of any living room space, and give in ambience for when you're either watching TV or just chilling with family. I'm using these Nano Leaf RGB light strips behind the TV and cabinet, and I think it gives a nice floating effect to the TV but also acts as a good lighting source for the room. I've also got these shapes from Nano Leaf which definitely give the place of character, and are a major talking point for my living room. These lights are also HomeKit enabled so you can control them from your Apple devices. Third is something that I think isn't prioritized enough, and that's the air quality in your home. I'll always recommend an air purifier, this is the never change 5 by shock, and I love it because the filter's last up to 5 years, and all you have to do is vacuum these trays every few weeks. It also has a percentage gauge on top to show you the air quality of your home. Now staying on the topic of cleaning a powerful vacuum that's easy to use and has some cool tech is the Dyson V15 detect. It comes with a soft brush head specifically made for hard floors which also has a built in laser to show you where the dirt is, but be careful because it can become addictive. For me though, it's now become a must have. Last but not least in order to control my smart home, some sort of smart speaker is needed. I'm using a few HomePod minis which I've dotted around the house, and this just makes it easier to control scenes and lights just using my voice. So those are my top 5 smart home tech products that I think would make your place just that much better.

transcript: Be careful with Alexa. If you have an Alexa device like this in your home, you will be shocked by what I'm about to show you. Go to amazon.com and on your profile, select your account. There is a menu quite hidden over here under Privacy and Settings, so click on Alexa Privacy and in this menu, click on View Voice History. Here you will find all your recorded voice history, like this one for example. Everything you say is being recorded, but what is really alarming here is that Alexa records things even when you're not directly talking to Alexa. transcript: I asked my mom if I could have a lady friend over today. She said okay, but only if she could stay in the room. Yeah, that wasn't gonna work for me. After a heated back and forth, we struck a deal. She'd lead the room, but only if she could set up the Arlo essential pantilindor camera to keep an eye on us. I told her Arlo is for protecting your home, not for spying on your dog's date, but a deal is a deal. Once the camera was set up and mom created a custom AI alert for any funny business, we texted Lola to kick things up. The date started off strong. We ran wild, burned off our energy, and then finally made our way to the couch for some snugs. But sure enough, mom caught the exact moment we got a little too close. We were busted in 2k, and you won't believe how she used the two-way audio. Hey, 2 feet apart, please. And she didn't stop there. She sent the incriminating footage to dad, but that backfired on her because he was far from upset. That's my boy. My mom definitely knows more and controls more with Arlo, but I found a way around it. Prevacy mode activated. We are so back in business. Comment below what would your mom catch you doing on camera.
